<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Szepligeti" authorityYear="1908" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Neocardiochiles" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Neocardiochiles" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Neocardiochiles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to the genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brulle" authorityYear="1846" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Heteropteron" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteropteron" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Heteropteron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1853" class="Insecta" genus="Wesmaelella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Wesmaelella" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Wesmaelella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and shares the following characters: eyes without setae; median areola on propodeum absent; notauli weekly impressed and posteriorly absent; scutellar sulcus without any crenula. However, members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Szepligeti" authorityYear="1908" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Neocardiochiles" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Neocardiochiles" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Neocardiochiles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brulle" authorityYear="1846" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Heteropteron" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heteropteron" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Heteropteron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1853" class="Insecta" genus="Wesmaelella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Wesmaelella" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Wesmaelella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by possessing pectinate claws; propodeum with median longitudinal furrow (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Neocardiochiles alexeyi sp. nov. A lateral habitus B wings C dorsal habitus D dorsal anterior head E propodeum and T 1 - T 2." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706716" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">2E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Neocardiochiles braeti sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E lateral mesosoma F dorsal propodeum and T 1." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706717" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">3E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Neocardiochiles chriscarltoni sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium and ovipositor sheath E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706718" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">4E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Neocardiochiles fasciipennis A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D ventro-lateral hypopygium; arrow: median longitudinal fold E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3" figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706720" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">6E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Neocardiochiles franki sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E dorsal propodeum and T 1 F hypopygium, arrow: median longitudinal fold." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706721" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">7D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Neocardiochiles victoriae sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706722" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">8E</figureCitation>
), posterior submarginal carinae, and carinate lateral margin (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Neocardiochiles alexeyi sp. nov. A lateral habitus B wings C dorsal habitus D dorsal anterior head E propodeum and T 1 - T 2." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706716" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">2E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Neocardiochiles braeti sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E lateral mesosoma F dorsal propodeum and T 1." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706717" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">3E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Neocardiochiles chriscarltoni sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium and ovipositor sheath E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706718" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">4E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Neocardiochiles fasciipennis A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D ventro-lateral hypopygium; arrow: median longitudinal fold E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3" figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706720" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">6E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Neocardiochiles franki sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E dorsal propodeum and T 1 F hypopygium, arrow: median longitudinal fold." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706721" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">7D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Neocardiochiles victoriae sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706722" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">8E</figureCitation>
); hypopygium with median longitudinal fold (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Neocardiochiles braeti sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E lateral mesosoma F dorsal propodeum and T 1." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706717" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">3D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Neocardiochiles chriscarltoni sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium and ovipositor sheath E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706718" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">4D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Neocardiochiles fasciipennis A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D ventro-lateral hypopygium; arrow: median longitudinal fold E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3" figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706720" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">6E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Neocardiochiles victoriae sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706722" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">8D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
Body 6.5-11 mm. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Head</emphasis>
: Antenna 34-40-segmented. Face width 1.36-1.73 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than its height. Interantennal space with well-developed median carina. Width of anterior ocellus 0.96-1.15 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than POL. Eyes bulged and without interommatidial setae (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Neocardiochiles alexeyi sp. nov. A lateral habitus B wings C dorsal habitus D dorsal anterior head E propodeum and T 1 - T 2." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706716" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">2D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Neocardiochiles braeti sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E lateral mesosoma F dorsal propodeum and T 1." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706717" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">3C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Neocardiochiles chriscarltoni sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium and ovipositor sheath E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706718" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">4C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Neocardiochiles fasciipennis A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D ventro-lateral hypopygium; arrow: median longitudinal fold E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3" figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706720" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">6C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Neocardiochiles franki sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E dorsal propodeum and T 1 F hypopygium, arrow: median longitudinal fold." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706721" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">7C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Neocardiochiles victoriae sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706722" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">8C</figureCitation>
); median width of eye about 0.90-1.32 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than the median width of gena in lateral view. Gena extended ventroposteriorly into sharp prominence. Clypeus 1.64-2.61 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than its height; clypeal tubercles absent. Mandible bidentate. Maxillary palpus six-segmented. Labial palpus four-segmented. Galea short. Glossa short. Occipital carina absent. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Mesosoma</emphasis>
: Notauli weakly impressed and absent posteriorly (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Neocardiochiles alexeyi sp. nov. A lateral habitus B wings C dorsal habitus D dorsal anterior head E propodeum and T 1 - T 2." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706716" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">2C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Neocardiochiles braeti sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E lateral mesosoma F dorsal propodeum and T 1." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706717" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">3B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Neocardiochiles chriscarltoni sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium and ovipositor sheath E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706718" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">4B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Neocardiochiles fasciipennis A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D ventro-lateral hypopygium; arrow: median longitudinal fold E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3" figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706720" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">6B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Neocardiochiles franki sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E dorsal propodeum and T 1 F hypopygium, arrow: median longitudinal fold." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706721" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">7B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Neocardiochiles victoriae sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706722" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">8B</figureCitation>
). Scutellar sulcus weakly impressed except for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kang" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Neocardiochiles" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Neocardiochiles alexeyi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alexeyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Neocardiochiles alexeyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., without crenula. Postscutellar depression absent. Pronotum entirely or mostly smooth with ventral longitudinal carina. Mesopleulon mostly smooth; posterior margin crenulate; precoxal sulcus absent (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Neocardiochiles chriscarltoni sp. nov. A antennae B mesopleuron." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706719" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">5B</figureCitation>
). Metapleuron mostly smooth. Propodeum 0.39-0.50 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than its median width; mostly smooth; with median furrow; curved submarginal longitudinal carina on propodeum present posteriorly; lateral margin of propodeum carinate (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Neocardiochiles alexeyi sp. nov. A lateral habitus B wings C dorsal habitus D dorsal anterior head E propodeum and T 1 - T 2." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706716" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">2E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Neocardiochiles braeti sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E lateral mesosoma F dorsal propodeum and T 1." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706717" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">3E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Neocardiochiles chriscarltoni sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium and ovipositor sheath E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706718" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">4E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Neocardiochiles fasciipennis A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D ventro-lateral hypopygium; arrow: median longitudinal fold E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3" figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706720" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">6E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Neocardiochiles franki sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E dorsal propodeum and T 1 F hypopygium, arrow: median longitudinal fold." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706721" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">7D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Neocardiochiles victoriae sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706722" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">8E</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Legs</emphasis>
: Basal spur on mid tibia 0.56-0.71 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than length of basitarsus. Hind tibia without apical cup-like projection; basal spur on hind tibia 0.48-0.62 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than length of basitarsus. Claws pectinate. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Wings</emphasis>
: Fore wing (RS+M)a vein present; second submarginal cell trapezoid; 1r absent; 3r absent; 3RSb evenly curved. Hind wing 2r-m absent; 2-1A absent. 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Metasoma</emphasis>
: T1 1.06-2.22 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than its posterior width, anterior width 0.53-0.83 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than posterior width, entirely separated with lateral tergum by suture; Y-shaped suture present. T2 nearly rectangle, 0.30-0.49 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than its posterior width. Hypopygium with median fold (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Neocardiochiles braeti sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C fore wing D anterior head E lateral mesosoma F dorsal propodeum and T 1." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706717" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">3D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Neocardiochiles chriscarltoni sp. nov. A antennae B mesopleuron." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706719" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">5D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Neocardiochiles fasciipennis A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D ventro-lateral hypopygium; arrow: median longitudinal fold E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3" figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706720" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">6E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Neocardiochiles victoriae sp. nov. A lateral habitus B dorsal habitus C anterior head D hypopygium E dorsal propodeum and T 1 - T 3." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.84937.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706722" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">8D</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor sheath nearly straight to slightly downcurved, as long as hind tarsomeres 1-3 combined as long as mesosoma, evenly setose except for base.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Neotropical region: Costa Rica, Ecuador, French Guiana, Mexico, and Suriname.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
The two species for which hosts are known attack pyralid and depressariid caterpillars on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Proteaceae" genus="Roupala" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Roupala" order="Proteales" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Roupala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Proteaceae" genus="Roupala" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Proteales" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Proteaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/jhr.77.50577" author="Dabek, EZ" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Hymenoptera Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" pagination="151 - 165" refId="B6" refString="Dabek, EZ, Whitfield, JB, Hallwachs, W, Janzen, DH, 2020. Two new reared species of Heteropteron Brulle (Hymenoptera, Braconidae, Cardiochilinae) from northwest Costa Rica, with the first definitive host records for the genus. Journal of Hymenoptera Research 77: 151 - 165, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/jhr.77.50577" title="Two new reared species of Heteropteron Brulle (Hymenoptera, Braconidae, Cardiochilinae) from northwest Costa Rica, with the first definitive host records for the genus." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/jhr.77.50577" volume="77" year="2020">Dabek et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
